segments.text: When you go about building a model of ecosystems or fish populations or whatever you should like to say, you rely primarily upon marine food chain systems to put this together?

Yeah, I think the answer is, yeah, the food chains and, of course, also the impact of the physical and chemical environment that you might say the abiotic factors that are a part of the ecosystem and are influencing abundance
trends and abundance and distribution and behavior.
So I think these things all ultimately have to be built into a model.
And food chain models are built at the present time.
There's no problem in building a food chain model.
I think the problem is really verifying its reliability and sensitivity.
And I think this is much more difficult.

particularly if one is going to use that model as a basis for judgment in terms of a decision of do I stop this fishery at this point, or do I leave so much food in a particular forage fish for marine mammals, et cetera.
Those sorts of questions require the empirical verification of the model.
And we're not in that position at the present time.
I think we're moving towards that sort of situation where we're measuring
a sufficient number of parameters over a sufficient time frame that we can essentially start to put a picture together.
But I say that's still downstream.
Now, I have a lot of hang-ups with some of our existing models.
And I realize that they're deficient in a lot of ways.
They're deficient in my view, not only in the terms of the fact that it's difficult to get the data, but also I have some real questions about the underlying assumption
some of the single species model, and even some of the multiple species models that have been put together.
I guess the care, I think, that needs to be taken in this is not to bind the hands of modelers.
Because I say this, I guess I'm a fairly applied sort of individual.
But still, I think that modelers must essentially
continue to be somewhat out ahead of the types of information that we can put into models.
They've got to develop and conceptualize models that provide a conception of what the system is likely to be like.
It's ultimately then up to us that are doing some of the verification of this is to ultimately see if we can find places where these things seem to fit.
And if they don't fit, what's wrong with the model and how that may ultimately be adjusted.
I think modelers have outstripped our capability of data input at the present time.
But I still don't think that ought to in any way prejudice moving ahead with the modeler.

I guess what I do think, though, that the minute the modeler thinks he is in a position to make judgments that are going to influence you, myself, and thousands of people in society, then we better be fairly sure that that model has some credibility.
I think a lot of models, both economic and biological at the present time, are pretty good for textbooks, but have very little utility and application.
Is there any exact way one can check a model?
That's what always bothers me.
I don't think there is any precise way, except that one starts to use a model

And I guess what I use the term that many of the modelers use is after you look at some of your data and you become fairly sure that you have a reasonable degree of precision and accuracy in your data, suddenly the model blows up on you.
Then you better decide there's something that the model isn't properly taking account of.
What kind of studies are now in progress at your institution?
Well, the institution now has been formulated into just what I told you I hope to do.
And by the way, there are four such groups now in the country.
There's one here in Seattle, one at Woods Hole, one down in Miami, and one in La Jolla.
And they sort of take large-scale ecosystems.
The La Jolla lab deals with the tropic, semi-tropical area.
We deal with the temperate Arctic environments.
And the same thing with Woods Hole on the other side.
They do it for the northern half
of the US in the same sort of environments.
And Miami does it in the south, east part of the United States.
And so we have a very broad range of studies under these conglomerate labs that now represent centers.
And we have been able to put the facilities.
We have probably some of the most modern electron microscopes in the world here at this particular center.
We probably have one of the only very highly sophisticated
electronic analysis of hydrocarbons and hydrocarbon components in this particular facility here.

And we do a lot of work for people all over the country in that particular in terms of a hydrocarbon analytical lab and where we essentially have facilities that examines electronically and looks and decides what the components are that we're looking at, both in the tissue and both in terms of the, well, various water samples, et cetera.
so that we have that capability.
We provide that more as a service rather than a scientific study.
In other words, we've got an analytical facility here in hydrocarbons that is really a lab that provides a national focus in looking at samples coming from all over the country.
The actual studies then on, for example, the fate and effect of, say, hydrocarbons is done by another group here of the scientists that uses the analytical facility as a major facility to get
some of their analysis run.
But we have, let's say, about six major areas that I'd like to point out to you that I think are important.

One, we have a very, very strong group that are looking at the whole area of essentially the environment in terms of contaminants in the environment or substances in their environment and their impact and fate and effect on the biological community.
And we're sort of taking a whole clinical approach in that.
We're not just running the so-called, well, we expose something to this sort of concentration level and 50% of the animal died so type of thing.
This is the type of thing that's been done to a large extent in many areas.
What we're doing is more setting up just like you would in a pathology lab in a hospital, where we're looking at the health of the animal,
We're looking at it at a cellular level.
We're looking at it at an organ level.
We're looking at it at the whole animal level.
We're looking at it how it impacts on the animal's capacity to behave and respond to various stimuli, et cetera.
So we're using a multidiscipline approach of physiologists, behaviorists, chemists, et cetera, and looking at a range of things in terms of that animal.
how much of the particular substance is ingested into the animal.
We want to know where it goes in the animal.
We want to know what cellular damage it does to the animal.
We want to know how the animal is capable of purging the toxic materials, if he is, and over what time frames, et cetera.
We want to know how that alters his capacity to live in his environment.
And that's a very strongly oriented program here under a fellow named Dr. Malins, who we're coming out with.
two books under academic press on this this summer.
That's a strong component of the program up here in looking at the impact of contamination in the ocean environment on the biota itself.
We have another very large group that's looking at the population structure and dynamics of the resources and the consequences of man's intervention, both in terms

of the mortality he imposes as a result of direct exploitation and the more indirect consequences that he imposes on that same group of animals through altering the environment, either in the estuary in terms of salmon, both in the freshwater environment or in the marine environment.
So their job is basically one of modeling what's going on in that whole world.
and providing us the information upon which we have direct input to the consuls for management decisions.
That's a very sort of applied thing where a certain number of reports have to come out on each year.
This population went up.
This population went down.
The complex is in this particular situation.
These are our clinical sort of determinations of the condition of the stock.
They're highly parasitized or not, this and that.
They're growing well.
They're not.
And these decisions are then ground into the management plans which the consuls are using to manage the resources throughout the northeastern Pacific.

We've got a big program in marine mammals with the same sort of complex of studies going on, of looking at sort of a broad range of their dynamics, what's happening to those in numbers, how man's impacting on those, whether they're natural, how the natural environment's impacting on those.
And those are fairly well wedded.

It sounds like I'm talking about two independent studies, but we have sort of a matrix approach, particularly the people that are in the ecosystem group that draw on the marine mammal people, that draw on the people that are doing the population studies, that draw on the people that are overdoing the studies in terms of environmental conservation, the group I talked to you about looking at hydrocarbons, et cetera.
We have another group that looks in a very utilitarian way at the whole concept
How do we develop good fish products?
The government has long had essentially a fisheries technology program that looks at preservation.

It looks at developing new products such as fish protein concentrate, new derivatives from oil that are useful in the industry or in agriculture, et cetera, so that we have a unit that essentially works in food technology as specific as it relates to marine organisms.
We have a group that we call, essentially, resource survey that does a lot of the basic survey.
And we've sort of separated this out because it's a mixture, really, of technicians and scientists.
They gather a lot of the basic data at sea that's being used by many people in the center.

And rather than having a lot of my scientists throughout the center that are very high well-paid scientists after they've had some of their early years exposure going to see all the time, we have a group of people that are essentially well-trained to develop experimental design.
How should a program be developed to go out here and sample species X?
They carry out the surveys and essentially accumulate the information and bring these back to the
the various units that are working throughout the center that are essentially applying that information in their science.
So it's really the at-sea group.
It does have a kernel of top scientists that know what that business is all about.

Underneath that, there's a broad range of technicians that are going to see taking water samples, measuring fish, taking age samples, looking at the gut of fish and looking for parasitization and collecting tissue samples, et cetera.
I probably missed something.
Oh, we have another group that's majorly involved in developing better tools to do the job.

There are, in other words, engineers, engineered biologists group that are saying if a guy over here needs this type of patrol to carry out his sampling, he takes it to them and essentially they put it together.
If you want to know how effectively that is, they do the measurements.
They set up the acoustical arrays for the system.
They set up the underwater televisions for the people, et cetera.
And I guess they're what we call gear technicians and gear specialists that essentially take on specific tasks.
For example, they're the group that's tied up in solving this porpoise tuna program down in California.
We've let our key engineer that's involved in design

of nets to go down there and design and work with the industry in designing a net that will essentially selectively take the tuna while at the same time having minimum impact on the porpoise of the area.

We have the same thing going on in the North Pacific where we've got a conflict between fishermen who fish for crab, don't want to see trawlers bring their nets through and kill off a lot of their crawls and trawls, excuse me, their crabs in a certain area.
These people then looking at designing, can I design a trawl that fishes one and a half meter off the bottom, takes most of the fish the trawler is interested in, but doesn't bother the crabs.
And this has been quite successful.

We're now in an era, I think, over the next 20 years, if we're really going to have effective utilization and not, while you're out trying to get one species, be destroying 15 others, is develop systems that are essentially what we call selective harvest methods.
in terms of having minimum impact or consequences on other elements of the biota.
And that's their major job.
Now, one of the gentlemen who worked for you, whom I talked to yesterday, is very optimistic about what amounts to mariculture.
That's one I missed.
I'm sorry I did that, because I support that program over at Manchester.
We have an aquaculture mariculture program.
We also, some of our food technologists are involved with this.
And again, I say we have a matrix of people.
We have some of our physiologists and nutritionalists that are over working with our people at Manchester, which is our facility to do this sort of work at the center here.
We also have one up at Oak Bay.
And we see some major possibilities, particularly over the long term, of making some major advances in this area.
And so I think you're reasonably optimistic concerning it too.
Is that fair to say?
Yeah, but I don't like to go out.

I think there's been a little, and I know in your part of the world, you've probably run into this, a little over-optimistic that you can do things overnight where you've got to develop the technical capability, the engineering capability.

You've got to get into the genetics area like we've done in many aspects of agriculture so that we ultimately are growing the right thing in the right environment with minimal cost and labor input into it.
You're giving advice to a young student.
What specific kind of oceanography would you ask him to go to?
Well, you know, I think the whole field is a tremendously interesting area, and there's so many interesting things going on in the ocean, I don't like to say one is more important than the other.

I'm going to sound like a contradiction, but I really think when I'm watching, by the way, I'm a professor over at the university, and I'm in the Institute of Marine Studies in the College of Fisheries.
I think the numbers of people coming out in the biological area are more than adequate, let's say, to fill the jobs.
In fact, we may be getting too many people in this particular area.
And I think it would be unfortunate that if we encourage more people than there are jobs, particularly if that's why they took the education.
Because I can just see us getting in a position with a large number of people trained up for PhDs and adequate number of jobs.
I see some other areas coming on, though.
The whole area of deep sea mining and the nodule business and the environmental consequences of that activity.
the engineering aspects of that type of activity.

I guess where I see the greatest demand, and this is going to be a very difficult task, in oceanography in the future, other than the pure sciences, is really people who are capable of dealing with multiple-use conflicts.

going to have conflicts between the people who want to mine and take sand and gravel and the people who want to develop transportation and facilities and people are going out after oil and essentially just a tremendous you might say invasion of the oceans in terms of both for its resources for recreational purposes and each one of these has an interaction and i guess

those individuals who have some perception in a broad sense of the multiple use conflicts and can draw on the scientists in the special specialities in an effective way are they going to be the people in terms of a managerial sense that are going to answer questions in a scientific sense i think all the all the areas are still extremely interesting and and i think they're moving ahead whether it's in biology physical oceanography geological oceanography
biological oceanography, I think the whole range is still pretty wide open.
I guess I'm just sort of drawn up in it.
I don't like to say, boy, there's only one interesting field in oceanography, because there isn't.
But I think oceanography and oceanographers have had to come to grips with something that some of them don't like all that well, is they're being forced more and more to orient
some of their activities toward problem areas.
And that big problem area I see is multiple use conflict over the next two to three decades.
